<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-UJ3bQ-kpvcxRjdzRv0eM2A" name="uam_logical_event,_ANn24AYSEeSyDIZvZjuaLg" guid="-UJ3bQ-kpvcxRjdzRv0eM2A" changeDate="2015-02-19T18:02:21.869-0500" version="7.5.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/concepts/uam_it_architecture_193573CD.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_XTWLgN_kEdynr9jlfK-aMA&quot;>Concept: IT Architecture&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;the idea of &lt;i>viewpoints (views and aspects)&lt;/i> that&#xD;
    are used to describe the IT architecture of a &quot;system&quot;. A logical (business) event is not one of the aspects, or&#xD;
    vertical slices through the architecture—it does not appear as a specific column in the UAM framework, but is part of&#xD;
    the &quot;Activity&quot; aspect. Events drive, and control,&amp;nbsp;the activities within the business.&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Note:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong>the term &quot;business event&quot; (as opposed to &quot;Business Event&quot;) is used here in the generic&#xD;
    sense—it applies to all levels of modeling: the Business, Logical and Technical Perspectives. See:&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/termdefinitions/uam_business_event_560E2C03.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_l3YHkMI7EeKSedlRPHdUIQ&quot;>Term Definition: Business Event&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Events&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    At the &lt;em>Logical Perspective&lt;/em>&amp;nbsp;level, the notion of event is used to identify and describe the&amp;nbsp;logical&#xD;
    level&amp;nbsp;events that are important in understanding how the business operates and how these events relate to&#xD;
    activities, tasks and processes. The Logical Process Model viewpoint supports the capture of events by describing the&#xD;
    business activities, and organizes them into a model. See: . At the logical level there are an expanded set of types of&#xD;
    events defined in UAM. There are generic Start and End events, to handle unknown situations (until they are refined and&#xD;
    properly defined), with more detailed and specific events defined for know situations. See the : &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_lpl_simple_AB1449E6.html&quot; guid=&quot;_uOZlsEWJEeOfR_FtRm9PUg&quot;>LPL&#xD;
    Summary&lt;/a>. The events defined and available for modeling in the Logical Perspective are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Conditional Events&lt;/strong> &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Catch&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Intermediate Boundary Interrupting&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Intermediate Boundary Non-interrupting&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Start (interrupting)&lt;br />&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>End&amp;nbsp;Event (unspecified)&lt;/strong>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Link Events&lt;/strong> &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Catch&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Throw&lt;br />&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Message Events&lt;/strong> &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Catch&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                End&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Start (Interrupting &amp;amp;&amp;nbsp; Non-interrupting)&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Signal Events&lt;/strong> &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Catch&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                End&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Intermediate Boundary Interrupting&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Intermediate Boundary Non-interrupting&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Start (interrupting)&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Throw&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Start&amp;nbsp; (unspecified)&lt;/strong>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Terminate&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Throw&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp; &lt;strong>(unspecified)&lt;/strong>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Timer Events&lt;/strong> &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Catch&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Start (Interrupting &amp;amp;&amp;nbsp; Non-interrupting)&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The &lt;em>Logical Perspective Language&lt;/em> has large numbers of events defined; see: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_lpl_E063ECCA.html&quot; guid=&quot;_eNHwsLhwEeSeNe6SxZNlbg&quot;>Supporting&#xD;
    Material: LPL Defined&lt;/a>.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Finding Events&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A starting point for finding events (and the start for business processes) are the relationships between Actors and&#xD;
    Activities (i.e. the &quot;system&quot;). A business event typically triggers the start of the business activity/process.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Also look at the activities and tasks within the system and the business process involved. Often business events are&#xD;
    needed to pass control between processes or between tasks.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Similarly if business entities have states defined then the state transitions may define possible business&#xD;
    events.&amp;nbsp;Also, any significant operations of a business entity are candidate business events.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
